<title>GABON: Producers plan new independent non-cocoa fat study.</title>
<headline>Producers plan new independent non-cocoa fat study.</headline>
<dateline>LIBREVILLE 1996-10-22</dateline>
<text>
<p>Cocoa producers plan to hire an independent consultant to produce a new study on implications of European Union plans to increase use of non-cocoa fat in chocolate, Ivory Coast's commodity minister said on Tuesday.</p>
<p>Guy-Alain Gauze told Reuters a delegation of officials from Ivory Coast, Ghana, Nigeria, Malaysia and Brazil would be sent to the European Parliament and the EU Council of Ministers in January to put forward producer country arguments.</p>
<p>&quot;The study will be independent and based on all considerations including legal, technical and scientific matters,&quot; Gauze said on the sidelines of a Cocoa Producers' Alliance ministerial meeting.</p>
<p>Producers are fighting an EU plan to allow up to five percent of non-cocoa fat in chocolate.</p>
<p>The CPA says the EU plan would cut world demand for cocoa by 200,000 tonnes a year but on Monday dropped opposition to use of non-cocoa fats in some other countries at the request of Malaysia.</p>
<p>In return, Malaysia rallied to the CPA view that EU consumers are rich enough to pay for pure chocolate.</p>
